Neonatal hypoxic-ischemic encephalopathy is a critical condition characterized by brain injury resulting from oxygen deprivation and limited blood flow during the neonatal period. The global market for neonatal hypoxic-ischemic encephalopathy is segmented based on diagnosis, treatment, end-user, and distribution channel. In terms of diagnosis, the market is categorized into physical examination and diagnostic tests. Physical examinations involve evaluating signs and symptoms, whereas diagnostic tests such as imaging studies and blood tests aid in confirming the diagnosis. Moving on to treatment options, therapeutic hypothermia is the gold standard intervention for neonatal hypoxic-ischemic encephalopathy. Other treatment modalities include medications for managing seizures, addressing brain swelling, and providing neuroprotective effects. Furthermore, end-users of neonatal hypoxic-ischemic encephalopathy solutions include hospitals, neonatal clinics, and others. The distribution channels for these products encompass direct sales and retail sales.

